                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology Lecture 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
The number of Grecian philosophers and<lb/>
the variety of opinions attributed to them<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">even in the</hi> first ages of civilization<lb/>
of the people demonstrated in striking<lb/>
manner the bias of public opinion towards<lb/>
study and the zeal with which science<lb/>
and information were sought for and<lb/>
pursued.<lb/>
The teachers of those times however in<lb/>
attempting universal systems formed a<lb/>
whole of which all the parts were<lb/>
necessarily imperfect.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
And the disciples either following <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">implici<add>tly</add>
            </del>
            <lb/>
implicitly or altering only in a small<lb/>
degree the dogmas of their masters, were<lb/>
constantly diffusing Theories in which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">truths</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and errors speculations and facts</hi> were<lb/>
indiscriminately blended -<lb/>
This was equally the case in all<lb/>
their departments of human enquiry<lb/>
if the records of the early doctrines brough<lb/>
brought down to the present times be<lb/>
supposed authentic -<lb/>
Filled with the sacred strength of<lb/>
genius the first sages seemed uniformly<lb/>
to have beleived that the human mind<lb/>
was capable of embracing all objects of knowledge<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
They delivered their opinions with the<lb/>
same confidence upon Nature and Man<lb/>
upon the divine and upon the human<lb/>
intelligence<lb/>
And they seemed to suppose that the<lb/>
paths of practical and as well as of<lb/>
abstracted sciences were to be developed<lb/>
by the mere powers of the unassisted<lb/>
understanding -<lb/>
But though all prone to hasty speculation<lb/>
in forming connections yet many admitted<lb/>
of appeal to experience and observation<lb/>
And it is to this circumstance and to<lb/>
this alone that we are whatever is<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
found true or valuable in their reasonings<lb/>
on <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sensible</hi> objects on Nature and on<lb/>
the Earth.<lb/>
That the school of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#person_609"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag1" type="person">
          Thales
        </name>
            </rs> had paid<lb/>
some attention to natural phaenomena<lb/>
is evident from the accounts given<lb/>
in the last lecture.<lb/>
And one of the fundamental axioms of<lb/>
the followers of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">pythagoras</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> was that<lb/>
the external <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">sign</del> signs of things<lb/>
were no less necessary to the discovery of<lb/>
truth than reason and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">analogy</hi> -<lb/>
The general doctrines of the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#misc_748"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag3">
          pythagoreans
        </term>
            </rs> concerning the appearances<lb/>
of nature had much more influence<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
on the early progress of science than<lb/>
any other system and the greatest<lb/>
instruct<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">ion</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ors</add> amongst the ancients and<lb/>
men whose opinions have come down<lb/>
to the present time most unimpared<lb/>
and with the greatest glory belonged<lb/>
to this celebrated sect of Philosophers -<lb/>
The History of their Illustrious founder<lb/>
is observed to so great an extent with fable<lb/>
and the marvellous that it is very difficult<lb/>
indeed to trace any of the real occurances<lb/>
of his life even his native place is unknown<lb/>
seven cities only contended for the honour<lb/>
of having given birth to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag4" ref="#person_035" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag4" type="person">
          Homer
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>; but as<lb/>
appears from the testimonies of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#person_1039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag5" type="person">
          Laertius
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
Lycus and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#person_1040"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="person">
          Josepheus
        </name>
            </rs> no less than nine<lb/>
different Nations considered <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="person">
          Pythagoras
        </name>
            </rs> as<lb/>
their Countryman.<lb/>
He was however generally supposed to be of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_1120"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          Samos
        </name>
            </rs> and his school is universally allowed to<lb/>
have been established about 500 years before<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#person_951"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag9" type="person">
          Christ
        </name>
            </rs> at <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#place_1119"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="place">
          Crotona
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
Like other ancient Philosophers He travelled<lb/>
in quest of information and it is said that he<lb/>
derived a considerable part of his knowledge<lb/>
from the priests of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag11" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs>, He at least<lb/>
learnt from them the Art of professing<lb/>
one doctrine to the public and of teaching<lb/>
another to his friends a refinement which<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
though it satisfied the people for many years<lb/>
did not in the end preserve him from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">persecution</hi>
            <lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag12" type="person">
          Pythagoras
        </name>
            </rs> if one may believe <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#person_602"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
          Plutarch
        </name>
            </rs> thought<lb/>
much; talked little and wrote nothing.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#person_1039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag14" type="person">
          Laertius
        </name>
            </rs> mentioned however the titles of some<lb/>
books supposed to be written by him: but<lb/>
upon very loose authorities;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#person_1041"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="person">
          Iamblichus
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#person_1042"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag16" type="person">
          Porphyry attribute to him
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
wonderful power over Nature and the faculty<lb/>
of predicting future events;-<lb/>
Their details however are not to be found<lb/>
in any of the more <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ancient writers</hi> and<lb/>
appear to be forgeries, and the greatest<lb/>
wonder faithfully recorded of him is that<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
he was able to keep his disciples silent<lb/>
for five years of probation.-<lb/>
The doctrines of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag17" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">pythagoras</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> concerning<lb/>
Nature as recorded by his followers mark in<lb/>
the strongest manner boldness of conception<lb/>
extent of knowledge possessing a mind filled<lb/>
with some of the most important truths of<lb/>
mathematical Science,<lb/>
He endeavoured to apply the principles<lb/>
of number and quantity to the explanation<lb/>
of the physical forms of Bodies and the laws<lb/>
of their changes - He considered matter as<lb/>
composed of certain different primary<lb/>
elements.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
He made their number five and assigned to<lb/>
each the form of a regular solid.-<lb/>
The elementary matter of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Earth</hi> He regarded<lb/>
as consisting of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cubes</hi> -<lb/>
The principles of water He imagined to<lb/>
have twenty <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sides</hi> -<lb/>
Air He regarded as consisting of eight sided<lb/>
figures<lb/>
Ether of twelve sided figures<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">And fire of pyramids -</hi>
            <lb/>
Having discovered the monochord He was<lb/>
so much delighted with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the invention</hi> as to<lb/>
search in every department of science for<lb/>
analogies to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Harmony</hi> and hence He conceived<lb/>
the elements of bodies were united in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">proportion</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
which may be expressed by the relations<lb/>
of numbers upon the musical scale; and<lb/>
that all the infinite varieties of matter<lb/>
were deducible from different orderly mixtures<lb/>
and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">combinations</hi> of the five Geometrical<lb/>
elements.<lb/>
This Theory of the composition of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Globe</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">though</hi> founded aupon assumptions which<lb/>
later experience has demonstrated to be<lb/>
visionary is nevertheless <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">is</del> exceedingly<lb/>
ingenious and very remarkable on account<lb/>
of the strong analogy that it bears to<lb/>
the system of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the moderns</hi> concerning<lb/>
Chrystalizations.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#place_155"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag18" type="place">
          Rome
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#person_869"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="person">
          de Lisle
        </name>
            </rs> and the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#person_307"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag20" type="person">
          Abbe H
        </name>
            </rs> in their<lb/>
late refined speculations upon the forms<lb/>
of minerals having supposed six primitive<lb/>
or Geometrical <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">elements</hi> capable like<lb/>
those of the Philosopher of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#place_1119"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag21" type="place">
          Crotona
        </name>
            </rs> of<lb/>
being united in various arrangements and<lb/>
and of being again resolved into their<lb/>
original forms -<lb/>
The few features that are develloped to us<lb/>
of the understanding of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag22" type="person">
          Pythagoras
        </name>
            </rs> in an age<lb/>
of darkness and of ignorance are at least<lb/>
sufficient to explain his great influence<lb/>
upon Philosophy<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">His discoveries even as imperfectly</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">displayed are of a high stamp</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
His discoveries even as imperfectly displayed<lb/>
are of a high stamp and it is not<lb/>
the least admirable trait of his character<lb/>
that he supported the idea of the roundness<lb/>
of the earth and its revolution round the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Sun </hi> -<lb/>
The first <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag23" type="person">
          Pythagorean
        </name>
            </rs> philosopher whose<lb/>
works are still in existance is <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#person_1043"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag24" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Ocellus</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
the Lucanian who is supposed to have<lb/>
flourished about 500 years before <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#person_951"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag25" type="person">
          Christ
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
in the beginning of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the</del>
            <lb/>
celebrated era of the triumphs of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Grecian Liberty</hi>
            <lb/>
in the beginning of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
His treatise <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">upon the universe</hi>; there is no<lb/>
reason to doubt its authenticity; and it is<lb/>
in the highest degree interesting as being<lb/>
the earliest Book composed upon a subject of<lb/>
pure <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">science </hi> -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag26" ref="#person_1043" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag26" type="person">
          Ocellus
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> like his master considered the<lb/>
Earth as composed of different regular parts,<lb/>
which imperceptible by our senses, are in a<lb/>
continued state of motion and of change -<lb/>
In this system<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">s</del> the solar fire is made the<lb/>
great agent in producing new arrangements<lb/>
of the bodies belonging to the Globe -<lb/>
This substance He regarded as the bond of<lb/>
union between all the other elements;<lb/>
which unite earth water Air and other<lb/>
in the highest degree interesting as being<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
From the successive union and seperation<lb/>
of the elements He explains the order<lb/>
of Nature; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in which</hi> though the parts are<lb/>
in continual change the whole remain<lb/>
one and unalterable.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#person_865"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag27" type="person">
          Heraclitus
        </name>
            </rs> of Ephesus and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#person_905"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag28" type="person">
          Parmenides
        </name>
            </rs> of <lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Elii</unclear> who flourished about the time of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#person_1043"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag29" type="person">
          Ocellus
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
possessed a similar doctrine. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag30"
                ref="#person_865"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag30" type="person">
          Heraclitus
        </name>
            </rs> not<lb/>
contented with supposing that Heat was the<lb/>
great active principle held that it was<lb/>
convertible into all forms of matter that<lb/>
the pyramid by its modification produced<lb/>
the other four regular forms of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag31"
                ref="#person_445"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag31" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">pythagoras</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
great active principle held that it was<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
The high importance assigned in the ancient<lb/>
systems to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fire</hi> is not indeed to be wondered at<lb/>
when the general appearances of Nature are<lb/>
considered.<lb/>
The Sun the source of the vivifying warmth<lb/>
belonging to our Globe is likewise the cause<lb/>
of the most numerous and most delightful of<lb/>
our sensations those of vision; by means of it<lb/>
water is raised from the ocean and diffused<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">through the Air</hi>; by means of it vegetation<lb/>
is produced and the whole of the surface<lb/>
of the Earth cloathed with verdure and<lb/>
ornamented with Beauty -<lb/>
water is raised from the ocean and diffused<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">through The Air;</hi> by means of it vegetation<lb/>
when the general appearances of Nature are<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
The contrast of winter with spring of Night<lb/>
with day of the ice clad mountains and<lb/>
steril snow plains of the North with<lb/>
the warm and fertil <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">hills</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">vallies</add> of the south<lb/>
must have effected in the strongest degree<lb/>
the minds of those whose imaginations <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">were</del>
            <lb/>
are constantly alive and the reasons and<lb/>
impressions similar to these which have<lb/>
impelled so many uncultivated Nations<lb/>
to offer divine honours to the principle<lb/>
of fire and to exalt it into a God seemed<lb/>
to have operated upon the early Philosophers<lb/>
in inducing them to consider it as the most<lb/>
active and energetic of the Elements and<lb/>
are constantly alive and the reasons and<lb/>
the warm and fertile <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">xxxxx</del> vallies of the south<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
as the material agent the most connected<lb/>
with the changes of things with motion<lb/>
organization and Life -<lb/>
A first intelligent cause of the order of the<lb/>
