            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag35"
                ref="#misc_455"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag35">
          Timeus
        </term>
            </rs> considered all ideas of the forms of<lb/>
things as prexisting in the supreme mind.<lb/>
and matter as modelled after those ideas in<lb/>
order and arrangement in consequence of the<lb/>
divine will - Earth he supposed to have<lb/>
been first produced then water then Air<lb/>
and last of All fire -<lb/>
And from their mixture in the Harmonious<lb/>
proportions of numbers he conceived that<lb/>
the universe was created in visible and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
tangible form perfect in its essence and<lb/>
indestructible as <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in</del> a whole the temple of<lb/>
the Creator having all its parts adapted<lb/>
to the great ends of life; and everywhere<lb/>
filled with animation with sentiment and<lb/>
with <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">life</del> Happiness: -<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
