               <name xml:id="tag49" type="person">
          Leucippus
        </name>
            </rs> according to Diogines <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag50"
                ref="#person_1039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag50" type="person">
          Laertius
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
conceived all things as formed of minute<lb/>
parts or atoms infinitely various in<lb/>
their figures and without regularity but<lb/>
constantly in motion; and endowed with a<lb/>
power of gravity or attraction inducing<lb/>
them assume the forms of Material bodies.<lb/>
From the attractive powers and their<lb/>
primary motions He supposed the changes<lb/>
of things to arise:<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
And on these foundations with the assistance<lb/>
of the word <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">necessity or chance</hi> He established<lb/>
his general system of which almost all<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the particulars</hi> are equally absurd with<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primary principles</hi>
            <lb/>
For he held that the stars were a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">colection</del>
            <lb/>
collection of atoms kindled by their motion<lb/>
