                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag56" type="person">
          Socrates
        </name>
            </rs> concerning<lb/>
Nature is delivered down to us<lb/>
and there is every reason to believe<lb/>
that this most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">excellent man</hi> saw<lb/>
all the imperfections of the methods<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Ancients</hi> and the vanity of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">their researches</hi>
            <lb/>
That he was devoted to experimental<lb/>
is evident from many testimonies<lb/>
one of the great accusations against<lb/>
him in his most unjust trial as<lb/>
quoted by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag57"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag57" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs> in his apology was<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">That he examined with unholy curiosity</hi>
