            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag58"
                ref="#person_907"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag58" type="person">
          Aristophanes
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag59"
                ref="#otherwork_311"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag59">
                  <hi rend="underline">"the Cloud"</hi>
               </bibl>
            </rs> is chiefly connected<lb/>
with his researches into the causes of natural<lb/>
things:<lb/>
And this production affords us almost <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">all</del>
            <lb/>
the only remains of his opinions on<lb/>
Natural philosophy -<lb/>
He is represented in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag60"
                ref="#person_907"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag60" type="person">
          Aristophanes
        </name>
            </rs> as attributing<lb/>
