and Majesty of Nature than the power<lb/>
and the force of water.-<lb/>
For this one principle as it were rules<lb/>
and commands all the other elements -<lb/>
It acts upon and dissolves the solid earth -<lb/>
It weakens and even extinguishes the devouring<lb/>
energy of fire. It rises into the air in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">vapor</hi>
            <lb/>
and forms clouds and mists whence lightning<lb/>
and thunder whence hail and snow and<lb/>
rain and the fertilizing dew<lb/>
Pliny attributes the tides to their<lb/>
real cause the effects of the sun and moon<lb/>
